10. Paperless Budget: For the first time in Independent India's history, the Budget for FY 2021-22 is paperless.

2. First Union Budget of Independent India: It was introduced on 26 November 1947. It was presented by the first Finance Minister R.K. Shanukham Chetty. It is to be noted that almost 46%¬† of the Budget or Rs. 92.74 crores were allocated for the defence services department.
1. First Union Budget of Colonial India: It was introduced on 7 April 1860 by the East India Company to the British Crown. It was presented by a Scottish Economist and politician James Wilson.

5. Black Budget: For the FY 1973-74, the Budget was presented by the then Finance Minister Yashwantrao B. Chavan and is called as 'Black Budget' due to a high budget deficit of Rs 550 crore-- the maximum until that time. The Budget followed the Indo-Pak war of 1971.

6. Maximum Union Budgets by a Minister: Former Finance Minister Moraji Desai presented the Union Budget a record 10 times, followed by former FM P. Chidambaram (9), former FM Pranab Mukherjee (8), former FM Yashwant Sinha (8), and former FM Manmohan Singh (6)
7. Dream Budget: The Budget presented by the then Finance Minister P. Chidambaram for the FY 1997-98 is known as 'Dream Budget' as it proposed to lower the tax slabs of personal and corporate taxes.
8. Change in time: In the year 1999, Finance Minister Yashwant Sinha changed the time for the presentation of the Union Budget from 5 p.m. to 11 a.m.
9. Longest Budget speech: Finance Minister Nirmala Sitharaman holds the record of delivering the longest Budget speech in 2020-- 2 hours and 42 minutes long.

PAN is a unique 10-digit number issued by the Income Tax Department of India and is mandatory for all financial transactions exceeding a certain threshold.

It is advisable to check with the specific bank for their requirements and to obtain a PAN card as soon as possible to avoid any inconvenience in the future. Having a PAN card also makes it easier for you to keep track of your financial transactions and to file your income tax

How can I download an e-PAN card?  You can download an e-PAN card in India by following these steps:  Visit the official website of the Income Tax Department of India  Click on the "Download PAN" link under the "Quick Links" section on the homepage.

Download your e-PAN card in PDF format by clicking on the "Download PAN" button.  Note: You need to have a valid mobile number registered with the Income Tax Department of India to be able to download an e-PAN card.
Also, ensure that you have a PDF reader installed on your device to be able to view and download the e-PAN card.  #PANcard #India #incometax

Every indian have to file income tax return? Not every Indian citizen is required to file an income tax return. Filing of income tax returns is mandatory only for individuals and Hindu Undivided Families (HUFs) whose taxable income exceeds the basic exemption limit set by the gov
It's advisable to consult a tax professional or check the official website of the Income Tax Department of India to determine if you are required to file an income tax return.

In addition to the basic exemption limit, there are other criteria, such as having a taxable income from house property, capital gains, or professional or business income, that may require an individual to file an income tax return.

PAN card, or Permanent Account Number, is issued by the Income Tax Department of India and is also valid for life, but must be updated if there are any changes in the personal details provided in the PAN card application.

If my spouse transfers 12,00,000 or more as a gift amount from his bank account to my bank account, do I have to pay income tax on that money?  According to the Income Tax Act, any sum of money received as a gift by an individual or a Hindu Undivided Family (HUF) is taxable

under the head "Income from Other Sources" if the total amount of such gifts received during a financial year exceeds Rs. 50,000.  However, there are certain exemptions available under the Income Tax Act, which means that certain gifts are not taxable even

if they exceed Rs. 50,000. One such exemption is that any sum of money received by an individual as a gift from his/her relative is not taxable. As per the Income Tax Act, a relative includes:  Spouse of the individual  Brother or sister of the individual

Since your father is your relative, any sum of money received by you as a gift from him is exempt from income tax, regardless of the amount. Therefore, you do not have to pay any income tax on the gift of Rs. 12,00,000 or more received from your father.

Is chennai Walk friendly ?  Yes. It is to a good extent.   I took a walk from Ekkaduthangal Metro station to Cafe Coffee Day at Guindy which is located on the railway station side of the GST. It would have been approximately 2 Kms and took around 25 mins to reach. There is pedestrian path all the way from the metro station till the Coffee day. However there were two issues I see. a very few places has been occupied by shops and the option to cross the mount road GST junction near the le royal meridian is not designed right.  I did not check the other side at the Alandur side.  Even though there is option for the two wheelers and four wheelers to cross the road from the meridian side and enter the subway below the kathipara, there is no proper signal. A signal would be helpful. Atleast pedestrian push button based signal will be good.   The real questions is how much do Chennai walk today. I myself have used to using bikes for a 500m distance for house hold purchase.    If I hadnot walked today, I would have hired a auto or took my vehicle to make this trip. This will increase my road presence adding to the existing traffic.   If a 10 people started waling for a 1 KM distance, we can remove one share auto from the road.  If 100 people started walking we could definitely remove one bus from the road.   Think of the cumulative effect of such a mass movement. This will help us with a better health and at the same time make Chennai more sustainable.   #walkchallenge #chennaiwalks #chennai #Chennaiwalkchallenge #1KMChallenge #Sustainability

Recently helped a startup reduce their burn from 83L to 65L  There are so many news we hear on daily basis startups cutting down the costs  In the form of layoffs, marketing budget and other things  Knew a company for a long while (Definitely can't share the name)  Who was having an average Burn of 83L in Jan-Mar month  Had a discussion with founders on various fronts where he was checking  How I managed to sustain my first 3 years of Picxele with not even single tools being used  Moreover with team size of 4-5 throughout  There are so many costs which keep on increasing as the company grows  And due to multiple reasons the founder cannot keep an eye  Ending up missing and spending money in places where few things aren't needed  And that's where in the last 3 months worked on from top to bottom along with him to bring the burn of 65L without even removing a single team member  Here are a few things which i did there  ‚úÖ Removed couple of Tools/Software which were not needed or replaced with some with better pricings  ‚úÖ Stopped the hiring for the entire company and open up the reshuffle option for the employees with some taking up more ownership  ‚úÖ Removing agencies which were charging a lot for a similar kind of work which got replaced by Part Time Gig Workers at Picxele‚Ñ¢ on task based mechanism  ‚úÖ Optimised the marketing budgets by removing the channels which were having higher CAC and focusing on the ones which were giving results and ultimately growth was never compromised  ‚úÖ Looking up on entire FY23 expenses and identifying the places where spent was happening which was of no use and company can eventually run without them  This helped the founder Increased the runway of more 4 months with total money he had in his bank  The very first thing I told him was that we will not remove any team members until anyone wants to go by themselve  It was that one thing which I also got excited about because when the company keeps growing  And you have VC money, you forget to cut down costs in places where it's not needed  Hence, we both realised Layoff is not the only solution to cut down the costs

Title: The Grit and Grace: A Startup Founder's Daily Battle for Survival  As a startup founder, life is far from the plush comforts of the corporate world. While our corporate counterparts enjoy the luxury of stable salaries, hefty marketing budgets, and grand offices, we face a different reality. Each day is a relentless pursuit to keep our company afloat, navigating through a sea of challenges that threaten to sink our ship.  Unlike the corporate world, where resources seem abundant, we must carefully manage every penny. Thoughts of monthly salaries for our dedicated staff, their families relying on us, and ensuring bills are paid on time weigh heavily on our minds. The responsibility we carry is immense, but it's a burden we willingly shoulder for the sake of our startup's success.  From paying office space rents to electricity and water bills, every financial obligation rests on our shoulders. Loans we've taken to fuel growth and vendor partnerships that help us thrive all demand attention. And if we have secured government grants, the paperwork and wait for disbursement add another layer of pressure.  Government grants, though vital for growth, often come with a complex claiming process. We need to use our company's funds first, making sure every document is in order, and then await the disbursal that can take ages. The bureaucratic hurdles can be daunting, and we sometimes wonder if we will ever receive the support we so desperately need.  Yet, as the founder, we wear a brave face, shielding our team from the burden we carry. We must remain composed and lead with determination, reassuring our staff that we are in control. Sleepless nights become a norm as we ponder over strategies to secure the monthly payroll and keep the ship steady in turbulent waters.  But amidst the storm, we find strength in our team, the united force propelling our startup forward. Our staff might not always see the sleepless nights or feel the pressure we endure, but they witness our dedication and commitment to their wellbeing and the company's survival. It's not just about surviving; it's about thriving in the face of adversity and celebrating the triumphs that come our way.  So, to all startup founders, take heart and remember that every storm will pass. Your unwavering determination and courage are steering your ship towards calmer waters. Together, we will weather the storms and emerge stronger, celebrating the sweet taste of success as one united force.

Dubai native here.  Noticed from the replies a lot of people think Dubai runs on oil, that's simply not true. It relies much more on fees/taxes, and customs, which make up more than 85% of its income.  The UAE federal gov does depend on oil for about half of its income but that reliance has been decreasing over the years as the state diversifies its investments and grows its non-oil sectors.  Back on Dubai, the below is an estimate breakdown of its income which is estimated to be $15.65 Bn  Gov fees: 57% (hotel stays, municipal fees, business licenses, fines, tolls, etc) VAT: 20% (We have a 5% VAT in the UAE) Customs: 10%  Oil revenue: 6% Gov investment returns: 6% Tax on foreign banks: 1%  The reason we have a better standard of living than most is that the city spends heavily on its infrastructure .. roads, hospitals, schools, luxury housing projects, bridges, solar plants,.. without mentioning constant law overhauls to add or change anything that isn't necessary or makes no sense anymore, or the ease of accessing government services   We're not a perfect city obviously and we have problems such as the heat, road congestions, and high prices in certain areas.. but its pretty difficult to live elsewhere once you're used to life here

Here are five essential considerations to ensure a successful real estate investment.  Financial Preparedness:  Prioritize a robust financial plan, ensuring you're financially ready to invest, including having a stable credit score, a clear budget, and understanding your borrowing capacity. This readiness sets the foundation for a secure investment journey.  Market Research and Due Diligence:  Conduct extensive market research and due diligence on the property, location, and surrounding area. Assess market trends, property values, growth potential, and neighborhood dynamics to make an informed investment decision.  Risk Mitigation:  Identify and mitigate potential risks associated with the investment. Plan for contingencies, evaluate market volatility, assess property condition thoroughly, and understand the legal aspects involved to minimize risks.  Long-Term Investment Strategy:  Develop a clear long-term investment strategy aligned with your goals. Consider whether you aim for rental income, property appreciation, or a mix of both, and plan accordingly to achieve your objectives.  Professional Guidance and Networking:  Seek guidance from real estate professionals, such as realtors, financial advisors, and legal experts. Building a network of professionals can provide valuable insights, advice, and support throughout your investment journey, enhancing your chances of success.
